<h2>What Gemini Search and ChatGPT Search Actually Do</h2>
<p>Both platforms retrieve live web data and generate answers. The mechanics behind each are fundamentally different.</p>
<h3>Gemini Search</h3>
<p>Gemini is built on Google's infrastructure. It has native access to Google Search, Google Maps, Gmail, YouTube, and the full Google ecosystem. When you ask Gemini a question, it queries Google's search index directly. The result feels like a Google search that writes its own summary.</p>
<p>Gemini processes multimodal inputs. It handles text, images, video (up to 1 hour), and audio (up to 8 hours) natively. For search-specific tasks, its connection to Google's real-time index means it accesses the freshest data available.</p>
<p>Google powers <a href="/blog/what-is-google-ai-overview/">AI Overviews</a> on approximately <a href="https://www.conductor.com/academy/aeo-geo-benchmarks-report/">25% of all Google searches</a>. Gemini's technology underpins these AI Overviews. Understanding how Gemini Search works is understanding how AI Overviews select and present sources.</p>
<h3>ChatGPT Search</h3>
<p>ChatGPT uses its own web browsing capability to retrieve real-time information. When you ask a search question, ChatGPT sends queries to the web, retrieves relevant pages, and synthesizes an answer from multiple sources.</p>
<p>ChatGPT generates <a href="https://www.conductor.com/academy/aeo-geo-benchmarks-report/">87.4% of all AI referral traffic</a> to websites. Its search function produces inline citations with clickable links. Users can follow those links to the original source.</p>
<p>The key difference: ChatGPT retrieves and summarizes. Gemini searches and integrates. ChatGPT pulls from the open web. Gemini pulls from Google's proprietary index and ecosystem.</p>
